  "texts": [
    "At that time, the concern with lack of transparency was related to NLP feature definitions and how they are combined to produce a score.",
    "Using LLMs creates a true \"black box\" with millions of parameters to interpret and explain.",
    "There are several approaches available to improve the explainability of AI scores; generally, these tend to be post hoc methods that demonstrate how different variables used within the model contribute to the final predicted score or classification so that the developer can better understand how these variables impact the final score as well as to look for any problematic or bias-contributing variables (for specific examples, see Boulanger & Kumar, 2024; Molnar, 2020; Riordan et al., 2020aRiordan et al., 2020b; Zhang et al., 2024).",
    "Bias in Automated ScoringHistorically, bias in educational tests has been evaluated by comparing scores from different demographic groups or subgroup populations, typically by checking for DIF (Holland & Wainer, 1993; Shermis, 2024).",
    "However, AI scoring introduces a different source of potential unfairness into the testing environment that did not exist when DIF methods were developed.To ensure that we can measure and address bias in educational testing, we first define the different types of bias and fairness (Johnson & McCaffrey, 2023)."
  ],
